steve jobs.
the people who are crazy enough to think they can change the world are the ones who do.
in 1976, jobs and wozniak began assembling
computers in the garage of jobs’ family
home. their first creation, the apple i, was
sold as a simple circuit board but gained
attention for its accessibility. soon after,
they founded apple computer. with the
launch of the apple ii, they helped ignite the
personal computer revolution and made
technology approachable to the masses.
early days.
before apple.
steve jobs was born in san francisco in 1955
and grew up in cupertino, california. he was
fascinated by electronics and design from a
young age, often visiting local engineers and
learning how things worked. as a teenager,
he met steve wozniak, a kindred spirit who
shared his love for building and
experimenting. this friendship would later
shape the course of personal computing.
starting apple.
his end.
over the years, jobs guided apple through
iconic innovations like the macintosh, ipod,
iphone, and ipad. he also played a crucial
role in shaping pixar into an animation
powerhouse. though he faced challenges,
including being ousted from apple in the
1980s, his return in the late 1990s marked
one of the greatest comebacks in business
history. tragically, jobs passed away in 2011
after a long battle with cancer, leaving
behind a profound legacy that continues to
shape technology and culture.
apple.
in 1984, apple introduced the macintosh, a
computer with a graphical interface that
redefined how humans interacted with
machines. yet, the years that followed were
turbulent. jobs left the company in 1985, and
apple struggled to find its direction. in 1997,
he returned, bringing clarity, bold vision,
and a design-driven philosophy that would
reshape the company.
apple’s early spark.
apple was born in 1976, when steve jobs and
steve wozniak built the apple i in a small
garage. it wasn’t just another machine — it
was personal, a computer for people rather
than corporations. the apple ii soon
followed, becoming one of the first widely
successful home computers.
the rise, fall and return.
innovation and legacy.
with jobs back at the helm, apple launched a
wave of iconic products: the colorful imac,
the ipod that changed music, the iphone
that transformed communication, and the
ipad that reimagined computing itself. apple
grew from a garage startup into one of the
world’s most valuable companies. after jobs’
passing in 2011, his influence still guided
apple’s journey, leaving behind a legacy of
innovation and simplicity.
unexpected lifeline.
in 1997, apple was on the brink of collapse after years of financial losses and dwindling
market share. in a surprising twist, longtime rival microsoft stepped in, announcing a
$150 million investment in apple. steve jobs appeared on stage at macworld with bill
gates beamed in via satellite, a moment that shocked the tech world. the deal wasn’t
just about money — microsoft also promised to continue developing microsoft office
for mac, ensuring apple’s computers stayed relevant for business and creative users
alike. for jobs, it symbolized a truce, a way forward, and the lifeline that allowed apple
to recover. this partnership, though uneasy, helped stabilize apple at a critical moment,
paving the way for the resurgence that would follow in the years ahead.
philosophy.
to jobs, design was not just skin-deep. it
was how something worked, how it felt, and
how it fit into people’s lives. he cared as
much about the invisible mechanics, the
intuitive interactions, and the flow of the
user experience as he did about the
materials and colors. form and function
were inseparable, and every detail mattered.
simplicity as a guiding
prinicple.
jobs believed that simplicity was the
ultimate sophistication. for him, design
wasn’t just about making things look good;
it was about removing everything
unnecessary until only what mattered
remained. every product, from the
macintosh to the iphone, reflected this
relentless focus on clarity and purpose.
design beyond aesthetics.
lasting influence.
jobs’ philosophy shaped not only apple but
also the broader world of technology and
design. his insistence on simplicity and
thoughtful design inspired generations of
designers, engineers, and creators to focus
on elegance, usability, and meaning. the
principles he championed continue to
influence products, services, and
experiences long after his passing.
quotes.
“stay hungry, stay foolish.”
“the people who are crazy enough to
think they can change the world are
the ones who do.”
“remembering that you are going to die
is the best way i know to avoid the trap
of thinking you have something to lose.”
“design is not just what it looks like
and feels like. design is how it works.”
“innovation distinguishes between a
leader and a follower.”
“sometimes life hits you in the
head with a brick. don’t lose faith.”
“quality is more important than
quantity. one home run is much
better than two doubles.”
“your work is going to fill a large part of your
life, and the only way to be truly satisfied is to
do what you believe is great work.”
steve jobs.
